&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence submitted by DECC (CCS42)[bold]1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Carbon Capture and Storage 
[normal](CCS) is a critical 
[normal]technology with potential to make a significant impact in reducing CO2 emissions from the power and industrial sectors in the UK and worldwide. CCS offers the 
[normal]opportunity
[normal] to continue to utilise fossil fuels, and enjoy the energy security benefits this brin
[normal]gs, but with vastly reduced emissions. CCS is also a critical part of meeting emissions reduction targets in a cost effective way. 
[normal]Whilst CCS is not currently competitive with other low carbon forms of generation
[normal] 
[normal]there is the potential for costs to fall si
[normal]gnificantly as deployment increases. 
[normal]Modelling in both the UK and internationally indicates it will be significantly cheaper to meet emissions reduction targets with CCS in the energy mix, rather than without. 
[normal]2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]However, there are currently
[normal] a range of
[normal] techn
[normal]ical and economic barriers to deployment
[normal] which impede projects coming forward independently in the UK
[normal] and elsewhere
[normal]. In recognition of the 
[normal]potential of CCS
[normal], the Government has introduced a comprehensive package of financial and regulatory support designed 
[normal]to 
[normal]help 
[normal]overcome these barriers.
[normal] The Commercialisation Programme will demonstrate the full integrated CCS chain at commercial scale, proving the technology and significantly reducing the 
[normal]commercial and financial 
[normal]risks currently associated with it. The Gove
[normal]rnment’s wider policies, as set out in the CCS Roadmap, look beyond the first projects and are designed to build a strong and successful CCS industry. 
[normal]3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]measures introduced by
[normal] Government 
[normal]are amongst the most 
[normal]comprehensive
[normal] anywhere in the world. 
[normal]The Gove
[normal]rnment is also
[normal] continually 
[normal]engaging with other countries worldwide
[normal] to promote CCS and learn from their experience. We are also in close dialogue 
[normal]with the industry in the UK to drive forward development and deployment of this technology.  The Government wel
[normal]comes the Committee’s investigation into Carbon Capture and Storage and 
[normal]the contribution it can make to the Government’s programmes in this area
[normal]. 
[normal]4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This is the Government’s evidence to the 
[normal]Energy and Climate Change
[normal] Committee
[normal]’s
[normal] inquiry into 
[normal]Carbon Capture and Storage
[normal], following a call for evidence on 
[normal]17
[normal] 
[normal]July
[normal] 2013. 
[normal]It provides an overview of the key issues and policies
[normal];
[normal] further detail is available in the various reports referenced throughout the text. 
[normal]5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Carbon Capture and Storage (CCS) is a chain of technologies designed to remove the greenhouse gas carbon dioxide (CO2) from power and industrial sources and transport it for safe permanent storage in saline aquifers or depleted oil and gas fields. 
[normal]I
[normal]t is
[normal] th
[normal]e only technology that 
[normal]has the potential to
[normal] 
[normal]turn high carbon fuels into genuinely low carbon electricity
[normal] and to decarbonise
[normal] many
[normal] industrial activities. 
[normal]It is a technology 
[normal]that the 
[normal]Government believes could play a significant role in 
[normal]low carbon 
[normal]electricity 
[normal]gener
[normal]a
[normal]tion
[normal].
[normal] Many Governments share this view 
[normal]and 
[normal]the UK is regarded as amongst the most supportive internationally.
[normal]Figure 1: Simple Carbon Capture and Storage Chain[bold]6.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]CCS is not a 
[normal]single, specific 
[normal]technology
[normal] as such
[normal], but 
[normal]the term instead covers several types of similar technologies 
[normal]used in each part of t
[normal]he 
[normal]CCS Chain
[normal].  T
[normal]he main variations being in the area of capture technologies which can be tailored to suit the application. Fo
[normal]r example, in the power sector
[normal] 
[normal]post-combustion capture[bold] 
[normal]involves the 
[normal]separat
[normal]ion of CO2
[normal] from the flue gasses
[normal] produced by the power station. This is the approach 
[normal]proposed 
[normal]at the 
[normal]Peterhead gas 
[normal]CCS 
[normal]project
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]7.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Another approach is 
[normal]Oxyfuel combustion[bold] whereby pure oxygen is used in place of air in the combustion process to yield a flue gas of highly concentrated CO2, a
[normal]s is proposed a
[normal]t the White Rose coal project
[normal]. 
[normal]8.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Alternatively where Syngas
[normal] (
[normal]a mix of hydrogen, CO and CO2
[normal])
[normal] is produced 
[normal]pre-combustion capture[bold] can remove CO2 to leave a combustible fuel. Finally, concentrated CO2 may be generated as an intrinsic part of the
[normal] production process
[normal], for example in gas processing
[normal] and in these cases 
[normal]inherent separation[bold] is used. 
[normal]Further details on the variety of technologies being developed within the CCS industry are available from the Zero Emissions Platform website
[normal].
[normal]9.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Governmen
[normal]t
[normal] does not believe that its role
[normal] is
[normal] to direct the development of 
[normal]these separate 
[normal]technologies that underpin CCS, 
[normal]and 
[normal]therefore
[normal] we
[normal] 
[normal]have
[normal] 
[normal]adopted a technology 
[normal]neutral
[normal] 
[normal]approach to CCS with an objective to create an environment which encourages technological 
[normal]development, removes barriers to deployment and encourages development of the industry
[normal] whilst leaving choices about technologies and projects to industry
[normal]. This is evidenced in the fact that the Commercialisation Programme has selected t
[normal]w
[normal]o projects
[normal] showcasi
[normal]ng different technologies
[normal] as preferred bidders
[normal].
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]10.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The development of CCS in the UK
[normal] is likely to contribute to economic growth 
[normal]as well as in the longer term facilit
[normal]ate
[normal] a competitive energy mix and the cost effective achievement of climate change objectives. 
[normal]11.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]We estimate that t
[normal]he 
[normal]deployment 
[normal]of commercial scale CCS projects could 
[normal]sustain 
[normal]4,000 – 8,000 jobs by 2020 in areas badly in need of growth. 
[normal] 
[normal]Public investment by 
[normal]the 
[normal]Government through the CCS 
[normal]Commercialisation
[normal] Programme
[normal] will lever further private sector investment
[normal] in these projects
[normal].  
[normal]12.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]More broadly the 
[normal]availability
[normal] 
[normal]of CCS 
[normal]to enable
[normal] commercially deployable low carbon source
[normal]s
[normal] of 
[normal]power 
[normal]generation is expected to secur
[normal]e
[normal] a
[normal] low-carbon energy mix, and reach our climate change targets in the most efficient manner. The E
[normal]nergy 
[normal]T
[normal]echnologies 
[normal]I
[normal]nstitute (ETI)
[normal] estimate
[normal] that successfully deploying CCS could cut the annual cost of meeting our carbon targe
[normal]ts by 
[normal]£32bn or 
[normal]up to 1% of G
[normal]DP by 2050.
[normal] 
[normal]13.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Having a diverse low carbon energy mix, including CCS, has further benefits including enhanced robustness of the electricity system, energy security benefits and increased 
[normal]competition between generators to the benefit of consumers
[normal].
[normal] CCS also of
[normal]fers the potential for flexible generation, 
[normal]especially important in a future low carbon mix dom
[normal]inated by inflexible 
[normal]or intermittent generation
[normal], and the opportunity to continue to utilise indigenous fossil fuel resources in the UK. 
[normal]14.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]CCS is also the only way for several important industrial sectors such as cement, steel and ceramics to decarbonise and is therefore likely to become critical to their competitiveness 
[normal]as those industries decarbonise
[normal]. That is why BIS and DECC are working wi
[normal]th academics and industry on a technoeconomic study in this important area to inform policy and financing regimes for industrial CCS. 
[normal]15.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]There is expected to be a strong global demand for CCS, with the I
[normal]nternational 
[normal]E
[normal]nergy 
[normal]A
[normal]gency (IEA)
[normal] estimating 
[normal]CCS
[normal] 
[normal]will co
[normal]ntribute one sixth of CO2 emission reductions required in 2050
[normal]. As an early leader, the UK CCS industry could export their expertise worldwide to the benefit of the UK economy. Research in this area
[normal] noted particular UK expertise in project management, en
[normal]gineering and financial and legal sectors. Further, the Technology Innovation Needs Assessment (TINA) estimated that CCS innovation could help create a UK industry with the potential to contribute further economic value of £3-16bn to 2050
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]16.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]CCS 
[normal]could play a
[normal]n important
[normal] role 
[normal]in 
[normal]avoiding
[normal] dangerous climate change
[normal], especially if it is successfully 
[normal]deployed 
[normal]across the world.   
[normal]17.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Global energy-related CO2 emissions continue to rise. In 2011 they increased by 3.2%, reaching a 
[normal]recor
[normal]d high of 31.2 gigatonnes
[normal], by far the largest source of global GHG emissions
[normal]. The continued expansion of fossil fuel generating capacity over recent years, despite strong advances in clean energy technologies worldwide, means that fossil fuels will inevit
[normal]ably play a role in energy generation for many decades to come. 
[normal]18.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]CCS offers 
[normal]the potential to reduce
[normal] the emissions associated with this fossil fuel use. A power plant with CCS could reduce CO2 emissions to the atmosphere by approximately 80-90% compared to an equivalent plant without CCS
[normal]. The IEA projects that CCS could contribute 14% of the total emiss
[normal]ion reductions through to 2050 in their 2°C scenario
[normal].
[normal]19.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]As is the case in the UK, CCS is currently the only large-scale mitigation option 
[normal]that could potentially
[normal] make deep reductions in global emissions from industrial sectors 
[normal]which 
[normal]represent one-fifth of to
[normal]tal global CO2 emissions and 
[normal]which are
[normal] 
[normal]projected to grow over the coming decades. The IEA estimate that almost half (45%) 
[normal]of the CO2 captured between 2015 and 2050 
[normal]will need to come from industrial applications and 
[normal]conclude 
[normal]that “Failure to utilize CCS tec
[normal]hnology in industrial applications poses a significant threat to world capacity to tackle climate change” 
[normal](
[normal]IEA 2013 p8
[normal])
[normal]. 
[normal]20.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]As long as fossil fuels and carbon-intensive industries play dominant roles in 
[normal]the global economy
[normal], CCS will be
[normal] a
[normal] critical
[normal] carbon abatement technology
[normal]. It
[normal] i
[normal]s also a cost effective solution, the IEA estimates that without CCS the cost of meeting a 50% global reduction in CO2 emissions by 2050 will be 70% higher
[normal]. Investing in CCS research, development and innovation now will p
[normal]lay an important role in reducing the costs of CCS around the world by developing cheaper and more efficient technologies and components, and contributing to characteri
[normal]s
[normal]ing storage sites.
[normal]21.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The benefits of CCS are therefore significant, not just for the UK b
[normal]ut for also for wider global efforts to prevent dangerous climate change. However, there are a number of barriers which have prevented widespread private sector deployment of the technology to date. 
[normal]22.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The individual components of the 
[normal]CCS chain 
[normal]use established technologies
[normal]. For example there is in excess of 6,000km of onshore CO2 pipelines in the USA
[normal] and CO2 has also been safely transported to stores offshore in Norway, with over 1MtCO2 stored per annum in Sleipner
[normal]. There is, however,
[normal] limited experience in full-chain CCS projects 
[normal]as there are
[normal] no large scale integrated CCS projects on power stations 
[normal]operational to date (although some are in advanced stages of construction)
[normal]. 
[normal]23.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Integration of the full chain at commercial scale presents bot
[normal]h technical and commercial challenges. For example
[normal], 
[normal]scaling up CO2 capture
[normal] technology
[normal];
[normal] 
[normal]the technical and 
[normal]commercial 
[normal]risks with 
[normal]the characterisation
[normal] 
[normal]and proving 
[normal]of 
[normal]CO2 stores
[normal];
[normal] and commercial risks around novel business structures. 
[normal]24.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The novelty of integration and scaling up means that first-of-a-kind full chain CCS projects 
[normal]face significant barriers to investment 
[normal]and CCS is 
[normal]not yet cost-competitive with other low carbon technologies
[normal]. Initial projects have high
[normal]er
[normal] capture costs and ener
[normal]gy penalties. Building the first transportation infrastructure and proving the first CO2 stores is 
[normal]capital intensive
[normal]. 
[normal]25.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Because CCS is not an established technology t
[normal]he current banking and private finance climate also presents some additional challenges. It
[normal] can be more difficult to secure finance for new projects such as CCS than 
[normal]in the past
[normal], 
[normal]or 
[normal]where 
[normal]finance is provided 
[normal]it can be 
[normal]associated with high
[normal]er
[normal] costs of capital. 
[normal]26.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]A strong carbon price should help strengthen the business case for CCS and counter the 
[normal]additional costs associated with the technology, however, the current price as seen in the EU E
[normal]missions 
[normal]T
[normal]rading 
[normal]S
[normal]cheme (ETS)
[normal] is not sufficient
[normal] by itself
[normal] to drive CCS adoption. 
[normal]27.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The UK Government has 
[normal]therefore 
[normal]designed its CCS policy to address these barrie
[normal]rs. 
[normal]28.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The Government has worked extensively to understand the barriers to deployment of the technology. 
[normal]Our assessment is that to be deployable on a scale necessary to contribute to the UK’s low carbon agenda CCS must be:
[normal]29.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Based on this we have developed a comprehensive package
[normal] of measures to bring forward the very first commercial scale CCS projects in the UK through our 
[normal]Commercialisation Programme
[normal], and also 
[normal]reduce or 
[normal]remove the barriers that stop projects coming forward independently.
[normal]30.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]In April 2012 
[normal]the Government
[normal] published the first UK CCS Roadmap setting out a comprehensive package to take us to cost
[normal] competitive CCS in the 2020s.
[normal] This submission does not attempt to cover the complete br
[normal]eath of measures set out in the Roadmap
[normal], full details of which are available i
[normal]n the report on the Department’s website
[normal].   
[normal] 
[normal]31.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The five key components outlined in the Roadmap are: 
[normal]32.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The CCS Co
[normal]mmercialisation Pro
[normal]gramme
[normal] aims to support practical experience in the design, construction and operation of commercial scale Carbon Capture and Storage.
[normal] By demonstrating the technology at scale, and the successful operation of the CCS chain both technically and commercially, the Competition will 
[normal]go some way in 
[normal]address
[normal]ing
[normal] many of the barriers currently hindering independent project development. 
[normal]33.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The Govern
[normal]ment has committed to making £1bn capital funding available
[normal] for up to two projects
[normal], and uniquely the UK is also providing operational support to projects through low-carbon Contracts for Difference.  
[normal]34.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The Competition was launched alongside the Roadmap in A
[normal]pril 2012 and attracted significant interest from industry, with 
[normal]eight bids submitted when the competition closed on 3 July 2012.  Following detailed analysis, four bids were taken forward into a bi
[normal]d
[normal] 
[normal]improvement phase in late 2012. From this group, two Pre
[normal]ferred Bidders were announced as part of Budget 2013, with the other two bidders being assigned Reserve Bidder status. 
[normal]35.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The proposals put forward by bidders that have been designated as Preferred Bids are: 
[normal]36.
[normal]&#xa0; 
