[normal]38.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]These FEED studies are invaluable not just for providing technical and economic certainty for the projects involved, but also for the detailed information they provide to wider industry and academics through our dissemination programme. 
[normal]Previous FEED studi
[normal]es have been made freely available through the Government’s Knowledge Transfer programme and have been a valuable addition to the body of knowledge on the subject
[normal].
[normal]39.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Bringing forward these large infrastructure projects is a complex process, requiring develo
[normal]pment of innovative solutions to issues that have prevented widespread deployment to date. The FEED studies will inform final investment decisions, expected to take place in 2015.
[normal]40.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The White Rose project has also been put forward for funding through the Eur
[normal]opean Commission’s NER300 second call, the only CCS project in Europe to 
[normal]do so
[normal]. 
[normal]The NER300 is a mechanism
[normal] to finance commercial-scale CCS and innovative renewable projects from the sale of 300m EU ETS 
[normal]allowances 
[normal]over two rounds. 
[normal]Award decisions are expecte
[normal]d by June 2014.
[normal]41.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]These projects, and the ones that follow, will be able to benefit from the Government’s development of a new market for low carbon electricity through 
[normal]the 
[normal]Electricity Market Reform (EMR) programme
[normal]. 
[normal]Far-reaching re
[normal]form of the UK electricity market is needed to meet our renewables and carbon targets while maintaining security of supply and minimising consumer bills.
[normal]42.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]EMR is a central component of the Energy Bill currently being considered by Parliament, and will addre
[normal]ss the need to attract unprecedented levels of investment in the UK electricity sector over the coming decades as we replace our ageing energy infrastructure with a diverse mix of low-carbon generation, and meet the expected increases in electricity demand
[normal] as sectors such as transport and heat are electrified.
[normal]43.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Contracts for Difference (CfDs) will provide efficient long term support for all forms of low carbon generation – including CCS.
[normal] They will provide the certain
[normal]t
[normal]y investors and developers need to proceed with projects. 
[normal]The UK is unique worldwide in 
[normal]planning to 
[normal]provid
[normal]e
[normal] on-going financial support through CfDs for CCS projects,
[normal] providing a route to market for projects and strengthening business cases
[normal].
[normal]44.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]During the summ
[normal]er we published a suite of documents on EMR for consultation. These provide key detail on the policy proposals including draft terms of contracts and ar
[normal]e available on the DECC website
[normal].
[normal] These reforms will provide certainty, as well as financial suppo
[normal]rt, fo
[normal]r the long term development of CCS in the UK.
[normal] 
[normal]45.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The UK 
[normal]has 
[normal]a 
[normal]world-
[normal]class 
[normal]CCS
[normal] research
[normal] base
[normal] 
[normal]and t
[normal]he Government is committed to supporting
[normal] this work. 
