[normal] 
[normal]49.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The UK has
[normal] le
[normal]d
[normal] the world in the development of a regulatory framework to facilitate CCS. The Government undertook a comprehensive review of the regulation necessary to enable CCS in 2007 
[normal]and
[normal] 
[normal]has 
[normal]quickly address
[normal]ed
[normal] barr
[normal]iers when they are identified. For example, adding po
[normal]wers to the Energy Act 2011 to address a barrier to the reuse of existing capital assets for the purpose of CO2 storage and transport. 
[normal]50.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]It is essential that the CCS industry has the right skills and supply chain it needs to develop. Therefore t
[normal]he Governmen
[normal]t is 
[normal]engaging with manufacturers’ organisations
[normal],
[normal] such as EEF and other partners
[normal],
[normal] to ensure UK companies are aware of the potential supply chain opportunities from the Commercialisation Programme, and beyond. 
[normal]51.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The Government also recognises the importance 
[normal]o
[normal]f long term regulatory and price signals for investor certainty. For this reason we have brought forward a ‘triple lock’ of 
[normal]policies designed to encourage deployment of CCS. These are (i) the National Policy Statement for Energy’s Carbon Capture Readiness 
[normal]requirements, and stipulation that there should be no new coal power plants over 300MW built without CCS
[normal]; (ii) the Carbon Price F
[normal]loor which gives an economic incentive to reduce emissions from fossil fuelled power stations; and (iii) the Emissions Perform
[normal]a
[normal]nce S
[normal]tandard which provides a regulatory backstop to the requirement of no new coal without CCS.
[normal]52.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]CCS projects
[normal] 
[normal]in the UK will be regulated by 
[normal]the Health and Safety Executive (HSE)
[normal].
[normal]  
[normal]53.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]HSE believes that existing legislation will allow for effective inspection and enforcement of health and safety standards associated with CCS projects. The Pipelines Safety Regulations 1996 also imposes general duties on all pipeline operators, including a
[normal]ppropriate design, safety systems, maintenance, suitability to convey fluids, construction and installation, and prevention of accidental damage. 
[normal]54.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]At onshore CO2 capture sites the co-location of qualifying amounts of substances will mean that operators wil
[normal]l be required to produce a safety case under the permissioning regime set out in the Control of Major Accident Hazards Regulations 1999 (COMAH). The COMAH Regulations are enforced by a body called the COMAH Competent
[normal] Authority, which
[normal] brings together 
[normal]the re
[normal]levant
[normal] government bodies of Health and Safety Executive (HSE) and Environment Agency (EA) in England and Wales, and the HSE and Scottish Environment Protection Agency (SEPA) in Scotland.
[normal]55.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]HSE has held direct meetings with each of the 
[normal]Commercialisation Progr
[normal]amme
[normal] bidders 
[normal]to discuss 
[normal]suitable and proportionate process safety based approaches to their projects. In particular
[normal],
[normal] the capture and offshore injection and storage stages will follow the same process design and safety principles that are already well estab
[normal]lished at onshore major establishments and offshore oil and gas installations.
[normal]56.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]D
[normal]etailed CO2-specific standards are under development 
[normal]relating to pipeline transport 
[normal]and design assumptions are being empirically tested in trials. Progress is also being made b
[normal]y the Health and Safety Laboratory and others in the modelling of CO2 dispersion in the event of a large-scale release. 
[normal] This work has informed discussions between 
[normal]HSE 
[normal]and the potential Commercialisation Programme projects. 
[normal]57.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]T
[normal]he 
[normal]Government 
[normal]is 
[normal]continually engag
[normal]ing
[normal] with industry to identify the issues
[normal] which may constrain CCS deployment
[normal] and work to develop solutions. For example, recogni
[normal]s
[normal]ing the concerns about costs
[normal],
[normal] we convened a CCS Cost Reduction Task Force
[normal] tasked with investigating the potential for cost reduction and recommending actions to secure these cost reductions.
[normal]58.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The Task Force 
[normal]concluded that UK gas and coal power stations equipped with carbon capture, transport and storage have clear potential to b
[normal]e cost competitive with other forms of low-carbon power generation, delivering electricity at a levelised cost approaching £100/MWh by the early 2020s
[normal]. In its Final Report
[normal], the Task Force also 
[normal]provided recommendations for both industry and Government on a
[normal]ctions that could be taken to help secure the cost reductions identified
[normal]. 
[normal]These are being taken forward by the newly established Storage Development Group, Commercial Development Group, Knowledge Transfer Network and through DECC’s wider CCS Programme.  
[normal]59.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The IEA forecasts that CCS could contribute 14% of the total emission reductions through to 2050 in their 2°C scenario, and that 
[normal]without CCS the cost of meeting a 50% global reduction in CO2 emissions by 2050 will be 70% higher
[normal].
[normal]60.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Norwa
[normal]y, the Netherlands, 
[normal]the US, Canada and Australia are 
[normal]amongst 
[normal]the leading CCS countries.
[normal] 
[normal]These countries incentivi
[normal]s
[normal]e CCS with a combination of policies and financial support. In total these countries have provided $5.6bn
[normal] in support for their CCS projects
[normal]. 
[normal]However
[normal], the 
[normal]current main 
[normal]difference between CCS projects in the UK and North America is that the latter 
[normal]intend to
[normal] 
[normal]use the captured CO2 for 
[normal]onshore 
[normal]Enhanced Oil Recovery (EOR)
[normal]. This allows them
[normal] to generate additional income t
[normal]hat
[normal] offset
[normal]s
[normal] capital and operati
[normal]ng costs
[normal], for example at
[normal] Boundary Dam in Can
[normal]ada and Kemper County in the US
[normal]. 
[normal]61.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Bringing forward the first com
[normal]mercial scale CCS projects is a challenge
[normal]. This is evidenced by the experience across Europe, where
[normal] 8
[normal] projects have been delayed or abandoned
[normal] since 
[normal]2010
[normal]. This despite 
[normal]CCS 
[normal]being
[normal] a central part of the EU’s energy and climate policy 
[normal]and introduction of 
[normal]a
[normal] CCS Directive covering both regulatory issues a
[normal]nd 
[normal]funding regimes through the EEPR and the New Entrant Reserve 300
[normal] (NER300)
[normal].  
[normal]62.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The Government is 
[normal]also 
[normal]engaging through regional, bilateral and multilateral relationships to collaborate and help overcome the challenges of commercial-scale CCS deployment.  We participate in a number of bilateral relationships as well as through international fora such as the
[normal] Carbon Sequestration Leadership Forum, the North Sea Basin Task Force, the Clean Energy Ministerial and the 4 Kingdoms CCS Initiative, working with countries facing similar challenges to 
[normal]CCS
[normal] deployment to address policy specific questions around CCS finan
[normal]cing and capacity-building.
[normal]CCS in a low carbon energy mix[bold] 
[normal]63.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The Government
[normal] believe
[normal]s
[normal] CCS could play a significant role in our future low carbon energy mix, and also in the global effort to reduce emissions and prevent dangerous climate change. Our policies are designed to give CCS the best possible opportunity to develop in the UK, with c
[normal]omprehensive financial and regulatory support as set out above. 
[normal]Our modeling suggests up 
[normal]to 12GW could be deployed by 203
[normal]0 and 40GW by 2050.
[normal]64.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Developing commercial Carbon Capture and Storage is an important part of the Government’s strategy for decarbonisin
[normal]g the power sector in line with the 2050 target at lowest cost. 
[normal]While 
[normal]our energy policies have been designed to bring forward all forms of low carbon electricity
[normal] so that that we are not 
[normal]dependent
[normal] on any one technology, 
[normal]i
[normal]f CCS is 
[normal]not successfully deployed t
[normal]here will be greater reliance on other low carbon technologies which would impose greater cost and risks 
[normal]in achieving decarbonisation.
[normal]   
[normal]65.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]This memorandum has set out the importance the Government attaches to CCS, the barriers to 
[normal]development of 
[normal]projects
[normal], and the extensive package of measures being introduced to drive deployment of CCS. Further information on any of these areas noted in this memorandum is available on request.
